<br>
At any rate, &quot;suru&quot; and &quot;shimasu&quot; are pretty much used like any other informal and formal versions of a verb.  Of course, as you may or may not know, you wouldn't use &quot;shimasu&quot; in the middle of a sentence (i.e. when it's not the last verb in a sentence) as you generally use the informal (dictionary form) version of a verb when it forms an internal part of a sentence.  Same with taberu/tabemasu and so on.<br>
<br>
'suru' (or shimasu) has quite a lot of usages based on its meaning of &quot;to do&quot;.  in the example you gave &quot;kimi wo shiawase ni suru&quot;, it is taking an adjective (shiawase - happiness) and making it into a sort of 'verbal adjective' - i.e. &quot;make you happy&quot;.  one of the most important usages for suru is in verbal nouns - that is to say nouns that can be made into verbs.  an example might include &quot;zetsubou&quot; which in and of itself means &quot;despair&quot;.  but adding &quot;suru&quot; to it would make it &quot;zetsubou suru&quot; - &quot;to despair&quot;.  and so on.<br>
<br>
anyway, like i said, i'll try and post those pages either tonight or tommorrow (i have class and work tommorrow from 8am until midnight so..... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
also: aru is used for NON living things, and iru is used for LIVING things.  iru is also used to form the present progressive form of a verb along with being a verb itself with a multitude of meanings (the most common &quot;iru&quot; - &quot;to live/exist&quot;).  aru can also be used to form a present progressive though with a slightly different connotation than that formed by using iru.  I'll have to look in my grammer book to be able to clearly explain the difference ( verb te form + iru is just the present progressive.  verb te form + aru  is something like &quot;present progressive for planned future usage&quot; or something... *blech*... i'm forgetting the basics.) Anyway, just use verb + iru for now and you'll be fine (taberu - tabeteiru, kuru - kitteiru, hairu - haitteiru and so on...)<br>
<br>
it's confusing.  dont' worry, it'll eventually all sort itself out for ya, just needs some time!<br>
